      "id": "theory_bin_to_hex",
      "title": "Binary to Hex: The Grouping Method",
      "content": "Converting binary to hexadecimal is much easier than converting to decimal! Why? Because each hex digit represents exactly 4 binary bits.\n\n**The 4-Bit Grouping Method:**\n\n1. Start from the RIGHT side of the binary number\n2. Group the bits into sets of 4\n3. If the leftmost group has fewer than 4 bits, add leading zeros\n4. Convert each 4-bit group to its hex digit (0-F)\n5. Combine the hex digits\n\n**Reference Table:**\n0000 = 0    0100 = 4    1000 = 8    1100 = C\n0001 = 1    0101 = 5    1001 = 9    1101 = D\n0010 = 2    0110 = 6    1010 = A    1110 = E\n0011 = 3    0111 = 7    1011 = B    1111 = F\n\n**Example 1: Convert 11010110 to hex**\n\nStep 1: Group from right: 1101 0110\nStep 2: Convert each group:\n  \u2022 1101 = 13 = D\n  \u2022 0110 = 6 = 6\nResult: D6\n\n**Example 2: Convert 101111 to hex**\n\nStep 1: Group from right: 10 1111\nStep 2: Pad left group: 0010 1111\nStep 3: Convert:\n  \u2022 0010 = 2\n  \u2022 1111 = 15 = F\nResult: 2F\n\n**Why This Works:**\nEach hex digit (0-F) represents values 0-15, which is exactly what 4 bits can represent (2\u2074=16 values)! This makes binary-to-hex conversion super fast - no multiplication needed!\n\n**Pro Tips:**\n\u2022 Always group from RIGHT to LEFT\n\u2022 Memorize the 16 conversions (0000-1111 to 0-F)\n\u2022 Common patterns: 1111=F, 1010=A, 0000=0"
    },
